INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1ffa8335-1374-4d87-b7af-2695d89be658',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Keras Data Loading — Batching, Shuffling, and Prefetching with tf.data$escape$,
  $escape$Keras relies on `tf.data.Dataset` as its backbone for efficient data pipelines. Rather than loading everything into memory, you build a lazy pipeline that transforms data on-the-fly.

Start with `tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices()` or `image_dataset_from_directory()` for structured inputs. Chain `.shuffle(buffer_size)` before `.batch()` — order matters. A `buffer_size` equal to your dataset size gives true uniform shuffling, but 1000–5000 is the practical sweet spot for large datasets.

Batching with `.batch(32, drop_remainder=True)` ensures static shapes, which is critical for `model.fit()` to avoid retracing the computation graph. Add `.prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)` at the end of every pipeline — it overlaps CPU preprocessing with GPU training, eliminating idle time between steps.

For augmentation, use `keras.layers.RandomFlip`, `RandomRotation`, and `RandomZoom` inside a `Sequential` preprocessing model and apply it within the dataset pipeline via `.map(augment_fn, num_parallel_calls=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)`. This keeps augmentation on the CPU and out of the model graph, so it's skipped during inference automatically when you pass `training=False`.$escape$,
  $escape$import tensorflow as tf
import keras

augment = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.1),
    keras.layers.RandomZoom(0.1),
])

dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((x_train, y_train))
dataset = (
    dataset
    .shuffle(buffer_size=2048, reshuffle_each_iteration=True)
    .batch(32, drop_remainder=True)
    .map(lambda x, y: (augment(x, training=True), y), num_parallel_calls=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    .prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
)

model.fit(dataset, epochs=20)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
