INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cff4c357-cf62-4b0a-9bb6-3a28df75b112',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Keras + scikit-learn — Plugging Your Model into Pipelines, CV, and GridSearch$escape$,
  $escape$Keras models don't natively speak scikit-learn, but `scikeras` fixes that. Wrap any `tf.keras` model with `KerasClassifier` or `KerasRegressor` and it becomes a drop-in sklearn estimator — fully compatible with `Pipeline`, `cross_val_score`, and `GridSearchCV`.

The key is defining a model-building function and passing it to the wrapper. From there, sklearn handles the orchestration: `StandardScaler` in a `Pipeline` will fit only on training folds during CV, preventing data leakage that's easy to introduce when preprocessing manually. `GridSearchCV` can tune both sklearn steps (e.g., scaler) and Keras hyperparameters (epochs, batch_size, units) in a single sweep.

Use `param_grid` keys prefixed with `model__` to target Keras-specific params. Set `refit=True` and `GridSearchCV` will retrain the best config on the full dataset automatically. This eliminates the boilerplate of manual fold loops and lets you benchmark Keras architectures with the same rigor you'd apply to an XGBoost model.$escape$,
  $escape$import numpy as np
from scikeras.wrappers import KerasClassifier
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
import tensorflow as tf

def build_model(units=64):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(units, activation="relu"),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer="adam", loss="binary_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

pipe = Pipeline([
    ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ("model", KerasClassifier(model=build_model, epochs=10, verbose=0))
])

grid = GridSearchCV(pipe, {"model__units": [32, 64], "model__epochs": [10, 20]}, cv=3)
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(grid.best_params_)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
